    <text>
        <body>
        	<div1 type="letter">
        		<pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0197"/>
        		<head>Jim to Mlle. Marcelle Guerin <date value="1915-10-27">October 27th ‘15</date></head>
        		
        		<opener>
            <dateline><date value="1915-10-27">October 27th ‘15</date></dateline>
        		</opener>
        		
            <p>
            I have just received your letter, 
            Marcelle, and find from it that
            Paul was right &mdash; that you
            have worked yourself into a bad
            condition.  Its a shame that the 
            A.A.  isn’t more careful.  Its a 
            crime to let you go on and
            on that way.  You should rest
            for a long time &mdash; but then,
            of course, my advice is foolish
            for it doesn’t count.  I hope any-
            way that you’ll be able to do
            what you want to put your-
            self in shape.  Above all I trust
            you wont go to pieces and have
            to quit for a too long time.  Its
            just your kind that’s making
            for Frenchwomen the most glorious
            reputation in the world and
            we musn’t [sic] have you be done up
            by the strain.  You shouldn’t
            go to the trouble of explaining 
            to me why you haven’t written.
            Its all aside from the main
            issue.  If I get your letters I’m
            fortunate &mdash; if I don’t then I’m
            unlucky and you either haven’t time
            
            <pb entity="DSSR_000001107_0198" n="[p.2]"/>
            
            or aren’t able or don’t care to write
            and that’s all there is to it.
            </p><p>
            I can’t tell when I shall
            be in Paris again as it depends
            on two factors over which I
            have no control &mdash; one is Ned’s
            return, and the other M. Thierry -
            Delanone’s success with the powers
            that be in this endeavor to
            get me sent to Avord instead
            of Pau.  The fellows at Pau
            say the outlook is hopeless.
            There are two hundred and fifty
            ahead of them and it looks
            as if they would be there
            for eight months.  Such a
            condition of affairs is impossible
            to entertain seriously.  I’ve got
            another fellow in the section 
            to make application.  He ought
            to be very good in my opinion.
            He came over to join the Canadian
            artillery but couldn’t get in being an
            American.  He was prize gunner in our
            Navy.  He’s not rough, either, and has
            plenty of nerve.  
            </p>
        		
        		<closer>
            <salute>More anon, and
            do take care of yourself.</salute>
            
            <signed>Jim.</signed>
            
            <seg type="postscript">
            S.S. Americaine No. 2<lb/>
            S.P. 84
            </seg>
        		</closer>
        		
